bring the same perspective,

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:48.080
or the same anger to it.

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:50.990
Because that's basically
where humor comes from is --

00:28:50.990 --> 00:28:55.310
the best humor comes from
being pissed off in a deep part

00:28:55.310 --> 00:28:57.290
of yourself about what's happening.

00:28:57.290 --> 00:28:58.590
Outrage. Injustice.

00:28:58.590 --> 00:28:59.890
All that stuff.

00:28:59.890 --> 00:29:01.310
I don't know if I feel
that way about any place

00:29:01.310 --> 00:29:02.610
that I felt about Florida.

00:29:02.610 --> 00:29:04.060
But thanks for the question.

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:05.360
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:29:05.360 --> 00:29:06.660
And I love your books

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:07.960
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Thanks.

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:09.260
Thank you so much.

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:10.560
Yes, ma'am.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:11.860
&gt;&gt; I was wondering what
is the favorite book

00:29:11.860 --> 00:29:13.160
that you've read and why?

00:29:13.160 --> 00:29:14.460
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Oh, I
mean, I get asked this.

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:17.510
I can't think of a single
favorite book that I've read.

00:29:17.510 --> 00:29:21.430
I think that -- as books
that influenced me a lot.

00:29:21.430 --> 00:29:25.120 position:56%
I've told -- it was a very -- one of
the many, but a there was a writer,

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:28.150
we had a great writer in north
Florida, name was Harry Crews.

00:29:28.150 --> 00:29:30.080
And he was out of his mind crazy.

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:31.440
And he taught at the
University of Florida.

00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:33.890
And he wrote several
highly acclaimed novels.

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:37.180
But one of which didn't get a lot
of attention was called "Car."

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:42.150 position:56%
And it was about a guy who eats and
entire Ford Maverick at a dealership

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:44.370
in Jacksonville from
bumper to bumper.

00:29:44.370 --> 00:29:46.190
They cube up with blowtorches.

00:29:46.190 --> 00:29:48.840
And it's a promotion,
you know, to sell cars.

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:52.610
And they've got the guy on
stage on a commode, basically,

00:29:52.610 --> 00:29:55.490
for the whole length of
the -- it's phenomenal.

00:29:55.490 --> 00:29:57.770
It's one of the funniest
books I ever read in my life.

00:29:57.770 --> 00:30:00.600
And I thought: he got
this published.

00:30:00.600 --> 00:30:04.220
He actually got this published.

00:30:04.220 --> 00:30:05.520
There's hope.

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:06.820
There's hope for me.

00:30:06.820 --> 00:30:08.120
But Harry Crews.

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:09.420
He was great.

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:11.230
And then I think Joseph Heller
had a big influence on me.

00:30:11.230 --> 00:30:13.120
"Catch-22" certainly did.

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:17.460
Because satire is a tough thing.

00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:19.580
It really -- you're
walking this tight rope.

00:30:19.580 --> 00:30:20.880
You want the suspense.

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:22.790
You want a story.

00:30:22.790 --> 00:30:24.590
You want characters
people care about.

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:27.230
You also have to have them
laughing on every page.

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:32.290
So, if you're off by a single
beat or a measure or a rhythm,

00:30:32.290 --> 00:30:35.500
if that makes sense, in your
sentences or in a paragraph

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:38.570
or in a scene that you're
writing, it's not funny.

00:30:38.570 --> 00:30:41.160
And readers know right
away when it's not funny.

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:43.070
So you agonize over that stuff.

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:45.040
Dialog becomes torture

00:30:45.040 --> 00:30:47.210
because you're not doing it
just to advance the plot.

00:30:47.210 --> 00:30:52.400 position:56%
You've got your own little seditious
agenda as a writer of satire

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:54.070
that you're trying to
sustain throughout it.

00:30:54.070 --> 00:30:58.340
So, yeah. I mean, it's -- you know,
there were not a lot of people

00:30:58.340 --> 00:30:59.640
who do it is what I'm saying.

00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:02.190
So, it's not like you
look around for a model.

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:04.850
And there's certainly not
a lot of people writing

00:31:04.850 --> 00:31:07.430
about giant Gambian pouched rats.

00:31:07.430 --> 00:31:10.990
So, I pretty much carve out
territory just for myself.

00:31:10.990 --> 00:31:13.030
Just for my own sick little world.

00:31:13.030 --> 00:31:14.330
Yes. Hi.

00:31:14.330 --> 00:31:16.720
&gt;&gt; I've read all of
your young adult books.

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:20.940
And I was wondering if there's
a certain event in your life

00:31:20.940 --> 00:31:23.720
that inspired your love of nature.

00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:25.020
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: That's
a good question.

00:31:25.020 --> 00:31:28.090
The young adult books, yeah,
they all kind of have that theme.

00:31:28.090 --> 00:31:29.900
Well, the first one I
did, I can tell you,

00:31:29.900 --> 00:31:32.780 position:56%
was "Hoot," I did several years ago.

00:31:32.780 --> 00:31:36.110
And that was like just like a
page out of my own childhood.

00:31:36.110 --> 00:31:38.260
It was about this story of
these little burrowing owls.

00:31:38.260 --> 00:31:40.800
They live in the ground.

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:42.100
They burrow underground.

00:31:42.100 --> 00:31:43.600
And I had them when I was a kid.

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:45.320
There was a bunch of them
that lived near my house

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:46.990
where my mom and dad lived.

00:31:46.990 --> 00:31:51.000
And one day a bunch of
bulldozers showed up.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.660
They were going to -- they were
going to put up a condominium.

00:31:53.660 --> 00:31:54.960
This is classic Florida.

00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:58.070
A condominium in Florida
called Hawaiian Gardens.

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:00.130
[ Laughter ]

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:01.510
And the signs were everywhere.

00:32:01.510 --> 00:32:06.830
And they had an actress, your
great grandmother might remember.

00:32:06.830 --> 00:32:08.130
Her name was Eve Arden.

00:32:08.130 --> 00:32:09.830
And she endorsed it.

00:32:09.830 --> 00:32:11.370
What was she doing there, anyway?

00:32:11.370 --> 00:32:12.670
I don't know.

00:32:12.670 --> 00:32:13.970
But they were selling
off the condos.

00:32:13.970 --> 00:32:15.690
And they're getting ready
to clear all this land.

00:32:15.690 --> 00:32:18.230
And my friends and I --
and we were about your age.

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:20.720
Every day we'd ride our bike
past the owls and they'd all be

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:22.030
out on their little burrows.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:23.570 position:56%
And their babies would be out there.

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:27.380
And we say, well they'd never do
anything with those owls there.

00:32:27.380 --> 00:32:28.730
They'd never hurt those owls.

00:32:28.730 --> 00:32:32.370
And they buried them alive.

00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:39.170 position:56%
Even at your age, I was highly upset
by that, that that could happen.

00:32:39.170 --> 00:32:40.570
It was so wrong.

00:32:40.570 --> 00:32:43.230
And so -- I mean, I
was pretty young.

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:47.060
But all around me concrete
was filling

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:48.630
in these place that I cared about.

00:32:48.630 --> 00:32:51.060
I lived out on the
edge of the Everglades.

00:32:51.060 --> 00:32:55.220
And so yeah, so that
experience stayed with me.

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:58.620
But when I decided to write this
book, when they asked me to do

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.620
"Hoot" I decided that
since it's my book,

00:33:00.620 --> 00:33:02.400 position:56%
it's going to have a happier ending.

00:33:02.400 --> 00:33:04.180
And that's the great selfish thing

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:06.390
about writing is that
they're my books.

00:33:06.390 --> 00:33:09.350
And they're going to
turn out the way I want.

00:33:09.350 --> 00:33:12.630
And something really terrible is
going to happen to the bad guys.

00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:13.930
Really bad.

00:33:13.930 --> 00:33:16.940
And I spend a lot of time
thinking up how to get rid of them.

00:33:16.940 --> 00:33:20.050
And I feel really good when I do.

00:33:20.050 --> 00:33:22.130
But thank you for asking.

00:33:22.130 --> 00:33:23.930
Thank you.

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:29.040
