When I got the chapters, they had
literally three different severed

00:35:54.100 --> 00:35:55.980
heads of Fidel Castro.

00:35:55.980 --> 00:35:57.280
Not just one.

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:00.690
I had to explain three
different dead Castros.

00:36:00.690 --> 00:36:02.700
It was a cluster, okay?

00:36:02.700 --> 00:36:04.870
Let me just leave that.

00:36:04.870 --> 00:36:09.360
It was what in Florida we would
call a goat wedding, okay?

00:36:09.360 --> 00:36:12.560
And Elmore Leonard,
God rest his soul.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:13.860
One of my heroes.

00:36:13.860 --> 00:36:15.160
He had chapter 12.

00:36:15.160 --> 00:36:16.460
I had chapter 13.

00:36:16.460 --> 00:36:17.760
And I got nothing from Leonard.

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:19.060
And I'm on deadline.

00:36:19.060 --> 00:36:20.450
We were serializing it
in the newspaper first.

00:36:20.450 --> 00:36:21.750
And I'm on deadline to write.

00:36:21.750 --> 00:36:23.050
I don't know what he's writing.

00:36:23.050 --> 00:36:24.350
I call him up.

00:36:24.350 --> 00:36:25.650
I said, "You've got
to send me something.

00:36:25.650 --> 00:36:26.950
I've got to start to writing."

00:36:26.950 --> 00:36:28.250
He goes, "Oh, God.

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:29.550
I forgot about this.

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:30.850
All right.

00:36:30.850 --> 00:36:32.150
I'll get to it."

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:33.450
And like a week later I get a
phone call saying, "Okay, Carl.

00:36:33.450 --> 00:36:34.750
Here's the deal.

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:36.050
I left you two dead bodies.

00:36:36.050 --> 00:36:37.350
They don't have a name.

00:36:37.350 --> 00:36:38.650
They could be anybody you want.

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:39.950
Two dead bodies."

00:36:39.950 --> 00:36:41.270
And I said, "Dutch, I need
like six dead bodies."

00:36:41.270 --> 00:36:44.420
I said, "If you had read what
I just got through reading,

00:36:44.420 --> 00:36:47.900
you would know how many dead bodies
I need to get out of this plot."

00:36:47.900 --> 00:36:49.430
But he left me the two.

00:36:49.430 --> 00:36:51.700
And then I just did my best.

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:53.410
But that's -- so anyway.

00:36:53.410 --> 00:36:54.710
Flash forward.

00:36:54.710 --> 00:36:56.600
Me, Dave Barry and
Elmore Leonard are

00:36:56.600 --> 00:36:58.800
on the Today Show sitting
on the couch.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:01.270
They've somehow decided
to make this a book.

00:37:01.270 --> 00:37:04.420
And we've mysteriously agreed
to go out and promote it.

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:05.720
We're sitting there.

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:07.020
I think it was Katie Couric.

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:08.800
And she says, "This looks"
-- she's holding up the book.

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:11.460
She goes, "This looks
like so much fun.

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:15.350
Would any of you ever entertain
any thoughts of doing it again?"

00:37:15.350 --> 00:37:19.860
Unprompted, unrehearsed, all three
of us looked at her and go, "No!"

00:37:19.860 --> 00:37:24.520
Boom. That's a true story.

00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:28.730
&gt;&gt; Sir, in any of your
books, is there a character

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:31.500
that you would dislike
or hate the most?

00:37:31.500 --> 00:37:33.740
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Who's
the most hated character?

00:37:33.740 --> 00:37:36.810
Boy, there was a book I
did called "Sick Puppy."

00:37:36.810 --> 00:37:38.260
And it was about a lobbyist.

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:40.230
I know you guys don't know
anything about that here.

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:41.530
&gt;&gt; I read that.

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:42.830
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Yeah.

00:37:42.830 --> 00:37:44.130
And you did read it?

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:45.430
How old were you when you read it?

00:37:45.430 --> 00:37:47.300
Where is your mom and
dad, by the way?

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:48.670
Hold on a second.

00:37:48.670 --> 00:37:51.050
How old were you when
you read that book?

00:37:51.050 --> 00:37:52.350
&gt;&gt; About 14.

00:37:52.350 --> 00:37:53.650
It was eighth grade.

00:37:53.650 --> 00:37:54.950
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Okay.

00:37:54.950 --> 00:37:56.250
All right.

00:37:56.250 --> 00:37:57.550
Anyway, you read the book.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:58.850
That's good.

00:37:58.850 --> 00:38:00.150
The guy's name was Palmer Stoat.

00:38:00.150 --> 00:38:01.450
You remember.

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:02.750
And he was, in my mind,
the world's worst --

00:38:02.750 --> 00:38:06.160
embodied the worst of the worst
of the lobbyists that I knew

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:08.960
and had written about
and covered in Florida.

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:12.310
And I thought this guy is the most,

00:38:12.310 --> 00:38:16.330
maybe the most despicable
human I'd ever thought of.

00:38:16.330 --> 00:38:20.050
And I -- but then after the book
comes out, I had lobbyists --

00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:21.860
I [inaudible] to them sometimes.

00:38:21.860 --> 00:38:23.500
And they loved the book.

00:38:23.500 --> 00:38:24.800
They loved the book.

00:38:24.800 --> 00:38:26.100
It's the damnedest thing.

00:38:26.100 --> 00:38:27.570
And they would say, "You
really nailed that guy."

00:38:27.570 --> 00:38:30.790
And they thought -- they always
thought it was their competition I

00:38:30.790 --> 00:38:32.090
was writing.

00:38:32.090 --> 00:38:33.390
They never saw themselves in it.

00:38:33.390 --> 00:38:34.690
But he was pretty bad.

00:38:34.690 --> 00:38:36.420
And something really bad
happened to him at the end.

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:41.350
I won't give it away, but I
didn't like him at all, very much.

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:44.970
Each book has somebody that I
really don't like very much.

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:46.940
And I can't help myself.

00:38:46.940 --> 00:38:50.490
But referring to Elmore
Leonard again.

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:52.560
And he always used to
talk to writers groups.

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:54.790
And then he would always tell
them, and we always know it's true.

00:38:54.790 --> 00:38:58.880
The bad guys are much more fun
to write than the good guys are.

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:00.540
You can have much more
fun with them.

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:02.320
I mean, your own personal code.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:03.980
Your own -- everything
goes out the window.

00:39:03.980 --> 00:39:05.920
And you can just go nuts
and have fun with them.

00:39:05.920 --> 00:39:10.300
And then dispense with them
as you see fit at the end.

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:11.600
So, that's another secret.

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:13.160
But thank you for mentioning that.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:14.740
Thanks. Hi.

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:16.860
&gt;&gt; Just a point of information.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:21.790
There's a place in New Jersey where
there is a mosquito administration.

00:39:21.790 --> 00:39:23.090
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: [Laughs] Yeah!

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:24.390
&gt;&gt; I kid you not.

00:39:24.390 --> 00:39:25.690
Every time we go to
Cape May we pass this.

00:39:25.690 --> 00:39:28.800
And we say, "Jeez, I wonder how
they're administering them."

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:33.210 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: In Florida it's
the Mosquito Control Districts are a

00:39:33.210 --> 00:39:34.510
political entity.

00:39:34.510 --> 00:39:37.310 position:56%
You actually have to go out and vote

00:39:37.310 --> 00:39:42.340
for your Mosquito Control District
Commissioners, based on what?

00:39:42.340 --> 00:39:44.510
What qualifies you, I don't know.

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:48.290
How much Benadryl you've
got in the house?

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:49.590
I don't know.

00:39:49.590 --> 00:39:53.460
But it's that -- and in the Keys,
traditionally, it was where --

00:39:53.460 --> 00:39:56.940
now, I'm saying traditionally --
it was where the deadbeat relatives

00:39:56.940 --> 00:40:00.610
of politicians who couldn't get
work anywhere else would get

00:40:00.610 --> 00:40:02.160
on a Mosquito Control District.

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:03.460
And they got a big salary.

00:40:03.460 --> 00:40:05.150
And they were in charge
of calling the planes.

00:40:05.150 --> 00:40:08.340
You know, we've carpet bombed
pesticides in the Keys.

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:09.640
I mean literally.

00:40:09.640 --> 00:40:10.940
You can't believe.

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:14.400
And they're flying under 500 feet,
dropping chemicals on your head.

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:17.500
All to kill this little
tiny bug because it is kind

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.470
of bad for tourism, you see.

00:40:19.470 --> 00:40:20.770
So, but anyway.

00:40:20.770 --> 00:40:23.450
In Florida, it's an
actual elected position.

00:40:23.450 --> 00:40:25.970
But it's, you know, it's great.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:29.170
&gt;&gt; We just have been
travelling and keeping track

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:31.980
of insane names of places as well.

00:40:31.980 --> 00:40:35.140
You know, so we'll joke around
and say, "This is my husband

00:40:35.140 --> 00:40:38.360
from Cucumber, West
Virginia" or whatever.

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:43.400
But my favorite, my favorite
YA book of yours is "Flush."

00:40:43.400 --> 00:40:47.050
Because I think what's really
exceptionally nice about it is

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:50.970
that the kids tell the dad, well,
we understand why you did it.

00:40:50.970 --> 00:40:52.270
But you did it wrong.

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:54.420
And then they proceed
to do it right.

00:40:54.420 --> 00:40:55.720
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Yeah.

00:40:55.720 --> 00:40:57.020
Well that's what --
you know, I spent.

00:40:57.020 --> 00:40:58.320
&gt;&gt; It's a fantastic book.

00:40:58.320 --> 00:40:59.620
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Yeah, I
mean, thank you so much.

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:02.440
But the think I was worried
about with the kid's books was

00:41:02.440 --> 00:41:04.630
that -- first of all the danger.

00:41:04.630 --> 00:41:07.460 position:56%
You never want to write down to
kids, because they're always smarter

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:10.010
and sharper than a
lot of the grown-ups.

00:41:10.010 --> 00:41:13.580
&gt;&gt; Which is why it's a good thing
inheriting all our problems.

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:14.880
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: Exactly.

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:17.610
They're going to be running the
planet, which is a good deal.

00:41:17.610 --> 00:41:23.150
But you want them to -- the way
they get the books is the humor is

00:41:23.150 --> 00:41:24.860
basically the same
in the kid's books.

00:41:24.860 --> 00:41:29.570
It's just got the same irreverent
smart-ass hopeless attitude

00:41:29.570 --> 00:41:30.870
in those books as I do.

00:41:30.870 --> 00:41:33.570
But I realize that they
love it when you make fun --

00:41:33.570 --> 00:41:36.080
kids love to read books where
you're making fun of the grown-ups.

00:41:36.080 --> 00:41:39.370
And then I realized that's what
I've been doing for 40 years

00:41:39.370 --> 00:41:42.260
in journalism in Florida
is making fun of grown-ups.

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:44.200
It was just a logical transition.

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:46.260
And they seem to dig it.

00:41:46.260 --> 00:41:50.550
&gt;&gt; We saw a great interview with
you on "60 Minutes" or "20/20."

00:41:50.550 --> 00:41:54.810
I forget. And one of my favorite
quotes from you is that if you want

00:41:54.810 --> 00:41:58.240
to change people, and
you rationalize --

00:41:58.240 --> 00:42:00.880
I mean, you talk rationally
with them,

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:02.240
they just harden their positions.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:07.350
And if you make them look
really stupid, they do change.

00:42:07.350 --> 00:42:08.650
Because they're embarrassed.

00:42:08.650 --> 00:42:10.070
I thought that was wonderful.

00:42:10.070 --> 00:42:11.370
&gt;&gt; Carl Hiaasen: They get it.

00:42:11.370 --> 00:42:13.320
You get their attention --
humor is a very effective way,

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:16.020
at least in the newspaper
business and in novels.

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:19.130
But in the columns as well, humor
is an incredibly effective way.

00:42:19.130 --> 00:42:23.360 position:56%
You can get up on a soap box and
scream all you want at a politician.

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:25.530
But when you start
making fun of let's say,

00:42:25.530 --> 00:42:32.390
the size of somebody's
fingers, for example, you know?

00:42:32.390 --> 00:42:34.050
Then they react in a way.

00:42:34.050 --> 00:42:37.790
But they -- they get it.

00:42:37.790 --> 00:42:42.390
You know, the object I think,
when you have a target,

00:42:42.390 --> 00:42:44.430
and satire always has a target.

00:42:44.430 --> 00:42:46.560
And the columns I write
have a target.

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:49.650
And I've always said from the very
beginning, you want as many people

00:42:49.650 --> 00:42:51.200
to think, "Oh, that's
what I've been thinking.

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:55.130
That's what I really -- I'm glad
someone else feels the way I do."

00:42:55.130 --> 00:42:56.840
And that's the one good
part of the column.

00:42:56.840 --> 00:42:58.700
And the other is you're really --

00:42:58.700 --> 00:43:02.860
you really want to ruin the day of
the person you're writing about.

00:43:02.860 --> 00:43:04.980
You really want to -- you
want to wreck their breakfast.

00:43:04.980 --> 00:43:06.730
You want them choking
on their Cheerios.

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:08.030
You want them to say, "Oh, my God.

00:43:08.030 --> 00:43:09.580
They're making fun
of me in the paper."

00:43:09.580 --> 00:43:12.110
And then you want them to face
their kids when their kids say,

00:43:12.110 --> 00:43:13.410
"Did you really vote for that?

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:14.710
Did you really do that?

00:43:14.710 --> 00:43:16.010
Did you really take that money?

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:19.870
Did you really sell out to big
oil or big sugar, whatever it is?"

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:22.820
Let them tell their own family that
that's what they do for a living.

00:43:22.820 --> 00:43:24.120
That's the job.

00:43:24.120 --> 00:43:25.420
And they ought to be ashamed.

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:27.200
They out to be sick to their
stomachs, some of them.

00:43:27.200 --> 00:43:29.440
And I love it when I hear
that I ruined their day.

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:30.890
It makes mine.

00:43:30.890 --> 00:43:32.190
Yes, hi.

